"Yes, chef. They must be on their way now, we gave them time to get rations from the mess." At 5:00 AM, the Exodus company was gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and began to speak.
"We're deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We need to support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the insurgency. From there, we'll have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," Shaw explained. "Assemble your units, and board."
The company dispersed, each member joining their unit, and the sergeants had them board the tanks. Cohren climbed onto one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he didn't know much about them. Sitting on the side, legs dangling, he adjusted his backpack and radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, does Harris still have Snowball?" Nemic asked as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren glanced at one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just distinguish the movement of a small chicken bobbing its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he still has it," Cohren replied as the tank's turret swung open with a creak to let his commander pass through.
"All the tanks were moving out," the calmly but clearly spoken commander in his helmet declared. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to advance. The Kronos that Cohren was on jerked as its brakes were released and it started moving to take its place in formation. The tanks deployed in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, haven't you?"
"Yeah, Operation Firestorm," Cohren replied. "We thought we'd be done in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is an understatement," Nemic said, joining the conversation. "They had more arms and men than we anticipated. They managed to take out the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Crap, we should be able to see it from where we are."
"Well, I'll hold my ground for the Federation," Orson said with a bit of provocation. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that new young recruits like you at 18 years old will take cover as soon as they hear a shot," Craith declared.
"I think we'll be set up soon," Cohren said with a laugh. Orson didn't continue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," Cohren's radio crackled. "We're detecting thermal signatures approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed onto the top of the tank and put on his optical goggles. By activating thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yeah, I see them," Cohren replied via his throat microphone.
"Enemies?" Natayla, the other recruit, asked.
"Impossible to say," Cohren declared. He activated his microphone and said: "Company Exodus, don't fire unless they fire first, let's let them out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures changed from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran towards something, grabbed it, and then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took firing positions.
"We have contacts," Shaw shouted into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. The bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while the soldiers jumped out of the vehicles to take cover behind them. A anti-tank missile passed by with a whir and crashed to the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris onto one of the vehicles. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew got out and dove for cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2 and &-, 25 degrees right, 275 meters." "Fire," the commander of the tank platoon shouted into the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flying towards the ridge and exploding, sending mud and rocks into the air.
"Send the Sentinels," Knoxx cried out, observing the ridge through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened, and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet stepped out. He shouted orders into a square microphone, and two Sentinels, or officially known as Sentinels, rushed out. Their thin metal arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?" Craith asked, watching them.
"It seems we're capturing them," Cohren said, as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of smoke and ash. Cries and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but stopped quickly. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots were dragging on the ground. Once safe with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain, collapsing into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked towards the individual, who was starting to get up. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," the Sentinel replied. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Would both of you kindly help us get rid of this man?"
